\begin_layout Subsection
Deployment notes:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Deployment instructions can be found in 
\series bold
sections 3.3.2-4
\series default
 of the User Manual (v1.2).
 Note that data acquisition will not begin until GPS contact is made,
 so one might want to initialize the units in an open area with clear sky visibility.
 Once the green GPS light is confirmed,
 the units can be moved to their indoor deployment locations without interrupting the acquisition cycle.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
According to the data,
 unit 583 began recording at approximately 13:30,
 and unit 579 began roughly one hour later,
 at about 14:30,
 due to a nondestructive technical deployment mishap by me,
 which delayed acquiring the GPS signal.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A manual intervention was performed to "
\series bold
mark
\series default
" the timeline.
 While originally intended as a calibration (moving the sensors at 
\begin_inset Formula $1\frac{m}{s}$
\end_inset

 along each axis),
 the sensors were instead moved exactly one meter in each direction at a nonspecific velocity.
 Consequently,
 these events serve as time markers rather than formal calibrations (see Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:marking-times"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

;
 Should have happened every day,
 but I repeatedly forgot to do it).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Relocation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On January 18,
 immediately after the marking,
 I replaced the seismographs (and,
 regrettably,
 didn't take photos).
 The 579 was placed in the corner near the wall,
 just out of the cabinet,
 and the 583 was placed on the floor right below its former position on the desk.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The seismographs were deactivated and collected by Aviv on the afternoon of Thursday,
 January 22.
\end_layout

