\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Time correction:
 
\series default
The clock as documented in the raw files seems to be Greenwich,
 so all times were manually shifted by 2 hours for the subsequent analysis and plotting.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that data from 
\begin_inset Formula $14/1$
\end_inset

's noon until 20:00 and from the 
\begin_inset Formula $22/1$
\end_inset

's 8:00 until afternoon were left out of this presentation.
 The data exists.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Orientation:
 
\series default
Both units were aligned as follows:
 the 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

-axis was directed along the zenith (vertical up),
 and the 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

-axis (refer to the orientation markings in fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Seismographs-first-config."
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) was directed toward the northern wall.
 Note that this alignment follows the local building grid and is not aligned with magnetic north.
 The two buildings are parallel,
 though,
 and also we expect symmetry of the noise to rotations in the plane (though observations are not overwhelmingly in support of this expectation,
 see plots in the next section).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All plots presented in this section represent 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

-axis data.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Sampling:
 
\series default
The sampling frequency was 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{s}=1kHz$
\end_inset

 throughout the acquisition in both units.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Periodic noise
\series default
:
 Both units show a 12–13 minute cycle,
 likely originating from an engine in the adjacent shed.
 Unit 583 records show it prominently in all days,
 while at unit 579 it shows much weaker and rather buried in the random background,
 though it is still clearly observable e.g.
 in fig.
 
