\begin_layout Subsection
Day-night variations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Comparing night time noise levels,
 represented by the 
\begin_inset Formula $0:30-6:00$
\end_inset

 window of January 15 series in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:15/2 dist. quiet"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 to day noise levels as represented by the 
\begin_inset Formula $11:55-12:00$
\end_inset

 window of January 17 series in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:17/2 dist. between cycles"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 we see no significant difference in strength,
 even in the shed.
 The night time was somewhat arbitrarily chosen to be fully outside the working hours (see the enhancement of noise at about this time in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:15/1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 and similar pattern in other days).
 The day time window was chosen so that it falls between the periodic source high noise cycles (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:17/1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Since the time span is very different,
 I don't attribute significance to the difference in the qualitative shape of the distribution between the days.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:15/2 dist. quiet"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:15/2 dist. work hours"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 2D spectral estimations are depicted.
 Long window averaging is given only to stress the difference between night and day variabilities - while the night noise of fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:15/2 dist. quiet"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 (also true for the calm work hours of fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:21th-morning"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 data,
 not depicted) is stable,
 so different hours produce similar noise,
 busy work hours noise produce highly variable hourly PSDs,
 as depicted in fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
