\begin_layout Section
Discussion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The seismic activity here overviewed is related to a resulting capillary waves signal via the relevant transfer function.
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Accuracy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The measurement inaccuracy is divided to a systematic 
\begin_inset Formula $1\%$
\end_inset

 uncertainty in the gain (table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Acquisition-Ch.-Specifications"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 ) and a random instrument error.
 With sensitivity of 
\begin_inset Formula $200V/\left(m/s\right)$
\end_inset

,
 an instantaneous dynamic range of 
\begin_inset Formula $120dB$
\end_inset

,
 and maximum signal of 
\begin_inset Formula $2.5V$
\end_inset

,
 the random error of the measurement process is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\text{random error}=\frac{2.5\cdot10^{-6}V}{200V/\left(m/s\right)} & =1.25\cdot10^{-5}\frac{mm}{s}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The error of the RMS of a large sample with independent small noise is proportional to the 
\series bold
value squared
\series default
 of the noise:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
RMS & =\sqrt{\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i}\left(s_{i}+b+e_{i}\right)^{2}}\\
 & =\sqrt{\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i}\left(s_{i}+b\right)^{2}}+\frac{1}{2}\frac{\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i}e_{i}^{2}}{\sqrt{\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i}\left(s_{i}+b\right)^{2}}}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is the seismic signal,
 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is the sensor's fixed unknown bias,
 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 is the error,
 and the cross term 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i}s_{i}e_{i}$
\end_inset

 vanishes when we sum over periods much longer than the dominant part of the spectrum.
 Since the random error is (as far as we know) Gaussian,
 this means that 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i}e_{i}^{2}\sim$
\end_inset

 the RMS is 
\begin_inset Formula $\lesssim10^{-7}\frac{mm}{s}$
\end_inset

,
 which is universally negligible with respect to the values in our data set.
 Therefore without doing an independent calibration of the seismographs,
 
\begin_inset Formula $1\%$
\end_inset

 error is our best estimate of uncertainty for the reported RMS values.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
For estimation of the error in individual points,
 including the reported segment maxima (at least when not representing identifiable events,
 but the analysis ignores this distinction),
 we use the independent noise sum rule,
 i.e.
 Pythagoras theorem.
 This is indeed required at least for low-valued maxima since,
 e.g.,
 
\begin_inset Formula $1\%$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $3\times10^{-3}\frac{mm}{s}$
\end_inset

 (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:20/1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) is 
\begin_inset Formula $3\cdot10^{-5}\frac{mm}{s}$
\end_inset

,
 which is comparable to the random error,
 and they are indeed mutually independent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
General remarks
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
During the day,
 the nearby construction site matched in noise the engine cycle amplitude over the wall,
 as can be seen e.g.
 in the graphs for unit 583 (shed) in fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:15/1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
