reference "fig:18/1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
As we see in fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:21/1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 which was Wednesday,
 work hours can be rather quieter than what we see in the graphs for earlier days.
 I didn't document the surrounding activities,
 but I suggest that this indicates that by far most of the noise that doesn't result from the nearby periodic source comes from the construction site,
 which was probably inactive at that day.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Conclusions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
All in all,
 while velocities of above 
\begin_inset Formula $10\frac{mm}{sec}$
\end_inset

 were observed (unrelated to my 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

markings
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

),
 not only is the RMS consistently 2-3 orders of magnitude smaller,
 but even during the work hours,
 if there is no building activity nearby,
 and with sufficient damping,
 I think we can expect the noise level on the shed's table to be at most hours similar to that of the floor,
 i.e.,
 
\series bold
consistently
\series default
 below 
\begin_inset Formula $0.05\frac{mm}{s}$
\end_inset

,
 which is negligible compared to our estimated signal of above 
\begin_inset Formula $10\frac{mm}{s}$
\end_inset

.
 Observe fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:20/1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:21th-morning"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 for references.
 This is 3 orders of magnitude below the expected wedge velocity,
 which should be of the same order of magnitude as the resulting ripple droplet velocities.
 Respective accelerations are in the order of 
\begin_inset Formula $1\frac{m}{s^{2}}$
\end_inset

 and above,
 while as seen in section 5,
 environment accelerations are about 3 orders of magnitude lower even in relatively noisy environments (
\begin_inset Formula $-60$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $-80dB$
\end_inset

 in power,
 see e.g.
 fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:15/2 dist. work hours"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 So insofar as we can bring the table vibrations to the level of the floor by adding damping,
 the error in the experiment resulting from the surrounding mechanical noise should be negligible.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
\start_of_appendix
Transfer function from base to water surface
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the following it is assumed that the mechanical phase velocities in the perspex much higher than the response time scales,
 and that the wavelengths of the base vibrations are much longer than the aquarium scales,
 so the walls move rigidly.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us set the coordinate system with the water surface as 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

,
 and origin at the middle of the horizontal cross section.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\aquaHeight$
\end_inset

 be the aquarium height,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\aquaLength$
\end_inset

 be its length and 
\begin_inset Formula $\aquaWidth$
\end_inset

 be its width,
 then the edges are at 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm\frac{\aquaLength}{2}$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm\frac{\aquaWidth}{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\velocityPotential$
\end_inset

 be the velocity potential,
 and let 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
u\left(t\right) & =\begin{pmatrix}u_{x}\left(t\right)\\
u_{y}\left(t\right)\\
u_{z}\left(t\right)
\end{pmatrix}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 be the walls velocity,
 which is assumed to be unaffected,
 to leading order,
 by the water response and fully determined by the base.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We begin by splitting the velocity field 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 into velocity potential and stream function derived components,
 
\begin_inset Formula $v=\nabla\phi+\nabla\times\psi$
\end_inset

.
 Then Navier-Stokes equations take the form
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\nabla\partial_{t}\vPotential+\nabla\times\partial_{t}\vStream & =-\nabla\left(\frac{1}{\rho}p+gz\right)+\nu\nabla\times\left(\nabla^{2}\vStream\right),
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where we use the incompressibility,
 or Laplace,
 condition 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla^{2}\vPotential=0$
\end_inset

.
 We require that the two components of the velocity field take care separately of each physical effect,
 then taking 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}$
\end_inset

 to be the pressure at the surface,
 it is enough to demand that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\partial_{t}\vPotential & =-\left(\frac{1}{\rho}\left(p-p_{0}\right)+gz\right),\label{eq:navier-stokes}\\
\partial_{t}\vStream & =\nu\nabla^{2}\vStream,\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

where we in practice chose a gauge.
 In the following we denote 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta p=p-p_{0}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
boundary conditions 
\series default
are:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\nabla f\left(x=\pm\frac{\aquaLength}{2}\right) & =\nabla f\left(y=\pm\frac{\aquaWidth}{2}\right)=\nabla f\left(z=-h\right)=\baseVel,\\
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

